\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Sorting Algorithm 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Patient Sorting
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:algo-patient-sorting"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following game: deal cards 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2},...,c_{n}$
\end_inset

 into piles according to two rules 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Can't place a higher valued card onto a lower valued card;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Can form a new pile and put a card onto it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the goal is to form as few piles as possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Greedy Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the natural order, place each card on the leftmost pile that fits.
 Note that by construction, at any stage during the greedy algorithm, top
 cards of piles increase from left to right.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Connection with LIS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Weak Duality
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In any legal game of the patience, the number of piles is larger than or
 equal to any increasing subsequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that cards within a pile form a decreasing subsequence and any sequence
 can use at most one card from each pile.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Strong Duality
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Min number of piles is equal to LIST.
 More over, the greedy algorithm finds both.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Each card maintains a pointer to top card in previous pile.
 The we can follow pointers to obtain IS whose length is equal to the number
 of piles.
 The by the weak duality lemma above, the sequence if one member of the
 optimal solution set of the LIS problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Implementations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This patient sorting algorithm could be implemented in 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n\log n)$
\end_inset

 running time by using an array of stack to represent the piles and binary
 search to bind the left most pile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Elementary Data Structures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Monotone Stack
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Find 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 -element subsequence that is lexicographically largest 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:monotone-stack-kth-elemnt-subseq"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Find [previous/next] [greater/smaller] element
\end_layout

